Add edit-license modal: adjust remaining time and note in-place

Task #7 — Edit license time and note. Admin can now adjust a customer's
remaining time and note from the dashboard or history page without
touching the database.

Backend (license_server/server.py):
- New POST /license/<id>/edit endpoint with three modes: "extend",
  "set", "note_only"; units minutes/hours/days; 10-year safety cap;
  rejects revoked/deleted/missing licenses with clear messages.
- Status-aware semantics:
  * pending  → adjusts duration_seconds (starts on first activation)
  * active   → adjusts expires_at (auto-expires if pushed into past)
  * suspended → adjusts expires_at so unsuspend sees the new remaining
    (caught by code review — initially I had this writing
    duration_seconds but unsuspend computes remaining from expires_at)
  * expired:
      - "extend" adjusts the existing expires_at (positive or negative);
        if result lands in the future the license auto-revives to active,
        otherwise it stays expired (per spec, extend = add to current
        expiry — caught by code review which rejected the previous
        "extend rejects non-positive on expired" behavior)
      - "set" revives from now with the given remaining
- /history dashboard data now also exposes expires_at_ts and
  duration_seconds so the modal can pre-fill correctly.

UI:
- Dashboard row gains an Edit button; history page also gains an Edit
  button on every editable status (active/pending/suspended/expired) —
  required because expired licenses are not shown on the dashboard,
  and the architect flagged that the “revive expired” workflow had
  no UI path.
- Modal moved into a shared partial _edit_license_modal.html and
  included from both dashboard.html and history.html. Modal styles
  moved to base.html so they apply on every admin page.
- Modal shows segmented mode toggle, amount + unit, note field, live
  result preview ("Result: 7d remaining time"), the absolute current
  expiry timestamp, AJAX submit, success/error toast, escape-to-close,
  click-outside-to-close, and focus restored to the triggering button.
- Dashboard exposes window.editLicenseOnSuccess to reuse its existing
  refreshData polling instead of a full page reload; history page
  falls back to the partial’s default page reload.

Verified end-to-end with curl across 12 cases including:
- pending +/- duration changes
- active extend/shorten/set with auto-expire on past delta
- suspended +3d correctly raising on-unsuspend remaining 5d → 8d
- expired +5d revive (was 2d ago) → active with ~3d remaining
- expired +1d (still 1d in past) stays expired
- expired set 7d → revived as active

No CSRF token added — matches existing admin POST pattern (revoke,
delete, unsuspend) which all rely on the SameSite session cookie.
